Python Syntax Basics ‚Äî Loops

Loops let your program repeat actions without rewriting the same code.
In automation, loops are everywhere ‚Äî renaming files, processing records, scraping pages, cleaning datasets, etc.

Python has two main loop types:
for loops and while loops.

üîÅ 1. For Loops

Used when you need to iterate over a collection (list, string, dict, set, file, etc.) or a range of numbers.

Basic Example
for i in range(5):
    print(i)


Output:

0
1
2
3
4

Looping Through a List
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"]

for fruit in fruits:
    print(fruit)

Looping Through a String
for char in "Python":
    print(char)

Looping Through a Dictionary
person = {"name": "Ron", "age": 41}

for key, value in person.items():
    print(key, value)

Looping With Index (enumerate)
names = ["Ron", "Jay", "Mike"]

for index, name in enumerate(names):
    print(index, name)

Looping a Specific Number of Times (range)
for i in range(2, 10, 2):
    print(i)


range(start, stop, step)

üîÇ 2. While Loops

Used when you don‚Äôt know exactly how many times you‚Äôll loop ‚Äî the loop runs as long as the condition is true.

Basic While Loop
count = 0

while count < 5:
    print(count)
    count += 1

Avoid Infinite Loops (Common Mistake)
while True:
    print("This runs forever")


Always add a break condition.

Using break to Stop a Loop
for num in range(10):
    if num == 5:
        break
    print(num)

Using continue to Skip an Iteration
for num in range(6):
    if num == 3:
        continue
    print(num)

Using pass as a Placeholder
for _ in range(3):
    pass  # do nothing (placeholder)


Useful when sketching code structure.

‚öôÔ∏è Real Automation Examples
Rename Every File in a Folder
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("C:/files")

for i, file in enumerate(folder.glob("*.pdf")):
    file.rename(folder / f"document_{i}.pdf")

Read a File Line by Line
with open("data.txt") as f:
    for line in f:
        print(line.strip())

API Pagination
import requests

url = "https://api.example.com/users?page=1"

while url:
    res = requests.get(url).json()
    process(res["data"])    

    url = res.get("next_page")  # stop when no next page

üß† Best Practices for Loops
Keep loops small & focused

Long loops ‚Üí messy code
Short loops ‚Üí maintainable automation

Prefer for loops when iterating collections

for loops are safer and cleaner than while.

Use list comprehensions for transformations
squares = [x*x for x in range(10)]

Avoid modifying a list while looping over it

Dangerous patterns cause bugs.

üìù Quick Reference
for item in collection:
    ...

for index, item in enumerate(collection):
    ...

for i in range(start, stop, step):
    ...

while condition:
    ...

break      # exit loop
continue   # skip iteration
pass       # do nothing
